{"key":"processedPost-14742580","value":{"id":14742580,"first":14696196,"last":14793097,"when":1310263480,"utime":"07/10/11 05:04 AM","content":"This is a long-standing problem around here, but an easy one to fix.<br /><br />Simply stack all the dishes in a single vertical stack after pouring.&nbsp; I pour in two stacks of ten each, and then place the stacks on top of each other and slip the plastic sleeve back over them, folding it at bottom to make a seal.<br /><br />Within two to three days, all the condensation has been reabsorbed into the agar.<br /><br />Never:<br />Turn dishes upside down.&nbsp; This causes a wall of water to fall on the culture when it's turned back over for use.&nbsp; In addition, it causes the moisture to fall out of the agar by gravity, compounding the problem.<br /><br />Never: <br />Leave a dish uncovered any longer than it takes to pour or inoculate that individual dish.&nbsp; I use the 5 second rule.&nbsp; If I can't get the job done in 5 seconds, I revise my technique so I can.<br /><br />Never:<br />Use glass petri dishes, because they suck for mycology.&nbsp; The plastic disposable are the way to go.&nbsp; After pouring, you put them back in the sleeve, with the sleeve inflated by air from the flow hood.&nbsp; When needed, you take only the amount of dishes you need from the sterile sleeve.&nbsp; I store them for up to a month this way until needed, at normal room temperature.<br />RR","title":"Re: Can't stamp out petri dish moisture"}}